The feeding of an obese child: does not take breakfast step and takes charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren weigh above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families who have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This shows once again how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround it is.
On the tables of obese children, for example, meat mills are found 50% more often than in families with children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner, according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of big kids, sports is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% answered that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
A survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted during the last school year and 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic participated.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and Unilever company.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have enrolled in this project.
One of the decisive factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight, or even obese children, is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough physical exercise.
"Only half of the children surveyed indicated for example eating breakfast 5 times a day - in case - lunch - tasting - dinner, which is a basic principle of good nutrition," one of the results of the survey said.
Without breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most families, each person has their own breakfast.
And the worst thing that has been noticed is that one-tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
However, breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families with obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed more often.
Almost every student – not to mention weight – drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of children surveyed do sports on a regular basis, but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food for yourself
Another part of the survey enabled selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet from options proposed according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and candy.
“The most alarming is a great preference for sweet lemonade,” the study’s findings said.
For lunch it is the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
The children did not want any fertilizers at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Cape on Health
The survey also showed that children are willing to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"In the course of a control of a group of survey participants who had filled out the questionnaire after the awareness session, 'Obesity is not a coincidence', a well-determined willingness to head for a healthy diet was set," the results of the survey indicate.
The most notable was, for example, with respect to sugary lemonades as children began to prefer drinking water.
Children most often cooked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sugary dishes and "knedliky" (Czech specialty of bread balls or potatoes).
