IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it was originally called Computing Tabulation Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a subsidiary of a company in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was the merger of four companies whose history is linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 chaired the Company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him lead the company.
The leader then shadowed the founder of the firm – it is on Watson’s ideas that until now rest on the identity and culture of society.
Watson ran the firm until 1952.
IBM, as its name implies, started with the production of all the machines possible for business and trade - from cheese and meat cutters to checkouts.
