How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel especially in the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in Eastern Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a slope for the west and travel to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered travel to the West, however, it was necessary to do the queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that, it wasn’t won yet.
The deal for currencies that was the condition for travelling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were consequently many country houses and cottages that the Czechs used to haunt and this habit lasts until now.
The Czechs’ journeys have been a major revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their maximum, the Czechs spent 4 million days abroad last year in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 as part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the western neighbouring countries has led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a trip to the Czechs was at that time to bring with them their own canned food, sausages, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the exchangeability of the Czech crown which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy the Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary have increased, which caused another important moment around 1997.
With increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours with air charter connections since 1997, which through contracts have dramatically reduced costs compared to previous ones.
At the end of the 90s, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the EUs that later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU removed visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to become fully within the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008, Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person on holidays abroad including annexes.
