In this novel story by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a tag during these few moments where, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the fogs of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, who awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book that he describes, accurately, as "an anti-history work."
It contains a few well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and equipment is found.
It’s not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a “book describing what it could look like.” There are “feelings, impressions, experiences and moods.”
"Beauty and Sadness" summarizes the experiences in wartime of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, from both sides of the war, from young schoolchildren and botanists to climbers, from doctors, ambulance workers and sellers.
Some of them will become heroes.
Some of the prisoners of war will lose members, become mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives here are vacillating like the beams of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are lighted up.
Peter Englund's book differs from traditional history books.
It denies the idea that World War I is summarized only by the terrible war of the trenches on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sadness" skillfully describes other war theaters: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under the husks; one passes Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the tse-tse-tse-fly is an untreatable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, such as a hurricane Katrina that puts the cord on.
When gunshots hold away, and you're a mother at home, do you stay or run away?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, not even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been overwhelmed by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors.”
