Facebook is packed with so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific precision — the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett’s team found that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to respond to their own survey. At their own level, their vulnerability, and questions related to their level of concern.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without leaving the office.
“This is a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young people and against immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screen.”
The DEMOS study is just an example of how Facebook has become the new indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Thinking groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that touch on health issues such as social trends, thanks to "Like", wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, the "supernova of data" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research works whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you might not be able to approach in the street.
“Earlier, when you were trying to investigate people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You should have gone to the party, but they would never have allowed you in,” Bartlett said.
“Facebook avoids all this – you have direct access to their information.”
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health and social problems.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunken exploits were significantly more likely to be alcoholic than students who were discreet about it.
