Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game similar to, say, friends, where the goal is to write: "I've had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the last six decades in such psychophy, in particular in a prestigious research project in a deep-seated university.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don’t always bleed, redden or stir.
Don’t conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to uncover.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast body and always emerging knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful to navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include, among other things, the management of deception.
Good liars are able to read others well, comforting them, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that the extravertises lie more than the introverts, that men say more lies "centered on them" while women say more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less to their spouses than to their mates.
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First of all, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what we call "setting the reference data."
This helps to provide a benchmark for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally shakes their feet permanently so as not to make unfair accusations when you see them shake their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for hints of verbal and non-verbal misleading behavior.
Consider these signs as red flags, not evidence of fraud.
