Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out in accordance with the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during flight and on the ground.
Meteorological conditions:
Reports in the ICAO mentioned appropriate conditions for take-off, and as the aircraft progressed towards the adjacent zone between DF and the State of Mexico, there were low-altitude fog layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the fog conditions the crew sought a lower altitude area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the aircraft's latest radar recording coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight trajectory.
Dispersion of aircraft residues in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact has taken place on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The aircraft's residue dispersion model suggests that the helicopter has collided with the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
In the location of the accident there is always no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above the average sea level, the ground presenting a slope that is from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful research in a larger area than the surrounding area, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the assumption that the impact took place under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
