The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and adolescents, called the 'Obesity Genetic Protocol of Children and Teens' which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the 20th Century National Medical Center’s Hospital of Specialties, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social assistants had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and undergraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the people with or without the right to participate, to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence for minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriental).
After reaching the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sportive Unidad Independencia (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sportive Unit Morelos (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the aim of this research and that e is to know the components and the importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays all participants of the anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics will be applied.
Cruz López noted that this research is the result of health professionals’ concern for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years, there was a 77 percent increase in boys' obesity and 47 percent in girls' obesity; there was also a dramatic increase in overweight," the IMSS specialist said.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent of Indo-American inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the overall evaluation of children, which allows to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
It even says that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood of suffering from metabolic disorders and even pre-diabetes.
The information is handled in a confidential manner, the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measures and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
Another reason is the high calorie intake, i.e. the largest intake of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - paste of meat with corn flour wrapped in leaves of corn -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high protocol content of fats and proteins.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cassis
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better efficiency, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 cassis each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who ensured that even if the process of construction and maintenance were reminiscent of the pavement.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Cassis, organized in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory of which he is responsible develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a higher temperament, but with a higher resistance to asphalt.
Herrera Nájera believed that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and therefore, the formation of cassis.
He explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the comterical co-veteral sound.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes hot-watering.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warns.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he reported, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass by generating effort, the latter allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If the asphalt had been modified, it would have spread better, according to the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one puts a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, of sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the bearing layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil wets, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to exit, which softens all the layers of the pavement and thus causes cassis.
In the process of forming a cassis, he says, the first one that breaks down is the rolling film and only later is the asphalt layer affected, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with aqueous maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle loading is another important factor for the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of pavement must always be related to vehicle loading and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cassis.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair cassis easily and without having to use high temperatures.
