Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Cali dactyloscopist has gone to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a CTI dactyloscopist from Cali passed to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano", comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven dactyloscopists working in the CTI’s local offices, this week was the “availability” tour of Eliasar González, a Puerto Tejada man who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliasar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man leading the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the site of the corpse, he did not recognize him by his physical appearance, because he was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But the fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian loup, ink, a pickup and a lantern, Eliasar compared the fingerprints of the corpse to those of the map.
His eye did not mislead him: he was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for confirming to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that he was the supreme leader of the Farc.
In search of the imprint
For a dactyloscopist from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González at a press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our job.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying the bodies, dactyloscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals have fake IDs or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher said that in a case of theft he had to remove part of the wall of a house, because in this place the thief had pressed his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
“The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint from all hands and identify the offender who had participated in different flights,” he recalls.
Fingerprints can also distract or confirm suspects in cases of homicide.
Recently, a dead man was found, with bottles of drink around him.
By way of the investigation, it was determined that a parent may be suspected of the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee that he's the killer, it's the place on the scene.
A CTI dactyloscopist explained that “the fingerprints of objects are extracted with chemical or physical reagents.”
When they appear, a pick-up machine or tape is used to pick them up.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the delinquents' database, or to the National Civil Registry.
“The problem is that there are still a lot of Colombians without papers,” the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
Like everything that shines is not gold, everything you touch does not necessarily become a fingerprint.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is realized.
