In fact, the year 2011 is expected to end with a 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (debit card, phone with SIM card...), to more than 6 billion units, according to the firm Eurosmart.
The most supportive segment is contactless technology that allows you to pay for public transport or to settle your purchases by simply approaching the card of a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards are expected to be sold worldwide, compared to 320 million a year earlier!
Their share is expected to continue to progress in 2012 (580 million expected units) and account for nearly 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Long after the Asia-Pacific region, Europe has gained ground for contactless payment.
Approximately 26 million Visa bank cards are already equipped with this feature and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa contactless cards have been deployed.
But the large surfaces put the double mouthpieces.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards this year.
To get to the top speed, banks now need to equip their customers.
“Two major French institutions have committed to systematically distributing contactless bank cards to their customers in the future,” said Gérard Nébouy, Managing Director of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing mobile payments
But this is only a first step towards the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
Few devices are now equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology that is essential for making transactions.
"They took the delay".
“But they should finally see a real growth next year.”
“We are counting on sales of 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012,” said Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The Agricultural Credit announced yesterday the launch of a test from December to June in Caen.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a case allowing contactless payment.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the general company, too, said yesterday it was preparing to market an offer allowing its customers to pay contactlessly with their mobile phones.
