On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Alger has now “acquired certainty”.
"The way both organizations operate and the intelligence services reports show that there is good cooperation," he said without further clarification.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger in January last year would have opened the doorways.
Kidnapped at a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day at the same time as several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the aftermath of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators had to find several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Axis terrorist
The analysis of past calls is oriented towards several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who has stayed long in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who says he is close to Aqmi and the sect.
“It’s an advance, but there’s no doubt more formal evidence to expect before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
