The Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has come into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, last Tuesday, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that directly connects, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe each year by a first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline is to be completed by the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third one on the same route is already mentioned.
For Gazprom, the timely and timely completion of this huge yard has the airs of victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose a bit of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to block it from accessing the Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the Hitler-Stalin alliance to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by providing its support to this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies there.
But this is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has managed to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose landfills are declining.
“This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically,” Fillon confirmed, inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economically important gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of reinforced concrete steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, mining fields dating from World War II had to be avoided.
“A hundred have been removed or destroyed, by caution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal serpent, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which does not interrupt on its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers resigned while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company set up permanently off their coasts.
“In the event of a mishap, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who planned the welding to see a leak every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, driven by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, wide by a meter of diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters per second, he provides accurate information about possible metal deformations.
The gas pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The flow of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for 20 years renewable, all of its gas transport capacities.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was ensured by 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their expenses, as only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The Baltic gas pipeline emerges in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificity of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elasticity, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (skin) which designates a varnish cotton used to cover banquets, for example.
This type of book was very popular with writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has been the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million currencies.
We are far from the confidential production of the early years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a buyer's portrait-robot, as the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees at its beginnings, now has nearly 100 and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her bookshops in bookstores, from the Fnac to small downtown shops, and has been able to impose her identity.
“We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition " Detour " where architects or artists exhibit their own booklet.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer covers... The brand boasts a wide range of supports.
A success that made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was redeemed by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of workers with disabilities so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of people with disabilities opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy set up in 2005, the unemployment rate of people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the whole population.
Discouragement?
"No," said Eric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
"The progress that has been made over the past fifteen years is considerable."
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.”
"However, there is still a lot to do."
It must be said that for the disabled unemployed, there are still many obstacles to accessing employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that complicate the return to employment, and that "are the nucleus of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for the target brakes.
The non-deed remains, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers surveyed had "a low level of knowledge of disability," with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities."
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6 per cent of disabled workers, set in a 1987 law.
The latest known figures, dating back to 2008, report a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of " taxed " institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011 from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
